"content": "<style>\nh1.thlex-title { font-size: 1.3em; margin: 0 0 0.4em; }\n.thlex-key { color: #888; font-size: 0.85em; font-weight: normal; margin-right: 0.4em; }\nnav.thlex-index { margin: 0.5em 0 0.75em; }\nnav.thlex-index ul { margin: 0; padding-left: 1.2em; }\nnav.thlex-index li { margin: 0.15em 0; font-size: 0.95em; }\n.thlex-section { margin: 0.6em 0; }\nh2.thlex-heading { font-size: 1em; margin: 0.5em 0 0.2em; }\nh3.thlex-subheading { font-size: 0.95em; font-weight: normal; font-style: italic; margin: 0.2em 0; }\n.thlex-language-sets { margin: 0.3em 0 0.3em 1em; }\n.thlex-language-set { margin: 0.4em 0; padding-left: 0.75em; border-left: 3px solid #e0e0e0; }\n.thlex-language { font-size: 0.8em; color: #888; margin-right: 0.4em; }\n.thlex-lemma { font-weight: bold; font-family: serif; }\n.thlex-translit { color: #555; font-style: italic; font-size: 0.9em; margin-left: 0.3em; }\n.thlex-refs { font-size: 0.85em; color: #444; margin-top: 0.15em; }\n.thlex-paragraphs p { margin: 0.35em 0; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.5; }\n.thlex-image { margin: 0.5em 0; }\n.thlex-image img { max-width: 100%; height: auto; }\n.thlex-abbr { border-bottom: 1px dotted #888; cursor: help; }\n.thlex-xref { color: #1a5fb4; }\nspan[data-bnType=\"bibleReference\"] { color: #1a5fb4; }\ntable.thlex-table { border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 0.9em; margin: 0.5em 0; }\ntable.thlex-table td { padding: 0.2em 0.6em; vertical-align: top; border: 1px solid #ddd; }\ntable.thlex-table tr:first-child td { font-weight: bold; background: #f5f5f5; }\nul.thlex-index-list { margin: 0.4em 0; padding-left: 1.4em; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.6; }\nul.thlex-index-list ul { margin: 0.1em 0; padding-left: 1.4em; }\n.thlex-index-key { font-weight: bold; font-style: italic; }\n</style><h1 class=\"thlex-title\" id=\"FAUNA:5.2\"><span class=\"thlex-key\">5.2</span> Frog</h1><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">References:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-sets\">\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">צְפַרְדֵּעַ</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(tsefarde‘a)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod7:27\">EXO 7:27</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod7:28\">EXO 7:28</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod7:29\">EXO 7:29</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod8:1\">EXO 8:1</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod8:2\">EXO 8:2</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod8:3\">EXO 8:3</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod8:4\">EXO 8:4</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod8:5\">EXO 8:5</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod8:7\">EXO 8:7</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod8:8\">EXO 8:8</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod8:9\">EXO 8:9</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps78:45\">PSA 78:45</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps105:30\">PSA 105:30</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Greek</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">βάτραχος</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(batrachos)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jude16:13\">REV 16:13</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/EsthGr19:10\">WIS 19:10</a></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Discussion:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p><figure class=\"thlex-image\"><img class=\"thlex-img\" src=\"images/WEB-0247_frog.jpg\" alt=\"WEB-0247_frog\"></figure>There is little doubt that the Hebrew and Greek words mean “frog&quot;. The plague of frogs mentioned in Exodus comes after the plague of polluted water. The frogs seem to have left the water and come into the villages. Since frogs eat flies and thus control fly populations, it seems likely that the death of the frogs was one of the causes of the next two plagues to trouble Egypt, namely gnats and flies.</p>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Description:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p><figure class=\"thlex-image\"><img class=\"thlex-img\" src=\"images/WEB-0248_frogs.jpg\" alt=\"WEB-0248_frogs\"></figure>The two most common frogs in the Middle East and Egypt are the Edible Frog <em>Rana esculenta</em> and the Spotted Frog <em>Rana punctata</em>. They are both about 70 millimeters (3 inches) long and are brown or olive-green in color. They live in the water almost all of the time and eat gnats, flies, and other waterside insects. They lay eggs, which hatch as tadpoles and gradually grow legs. The hind legs are much bigger and better developed than the front legs, since the hind legs are used for jumping.</p>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Special significance or symbolism:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>Frogs were considered unclean by the Jews and also by the Egyptians and Persians, who associated them with demons.</p>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Translation:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>Frogs are found all over the world, and there should be no problem in finding a local equivalent.</p>\n</div>\n</div>",
