"title": "Onycha",
"media_type": "Text",
"index_reference": "5.3",
"language": "eng",
"review_level": "None",
"content": "<style>\nh1.thlex-title { font-size: 1.3em; margin: 0 0 0.4em; }\n.thlex-key { color: #888; font-size: 0.85em; font-weight: normal; margin-right: 0.4em; }\nnav.thlex-index { margin: 0.5em 0 0.75em; }\nnav.thlex-index ul { margin: 0; padding-left: 1.2em; }\nnav.thlex-index li { margin: 0.15em 0; font-size: 0.95em; }\n.thlex-section { margin: 0.6em 0; }\nh2.thlex-heading { font-size: 1em; margin: 0.5em 0 0.2em; }\nh3.thlex-subheading { font-size: 0.95em; font-weight: normal; font-style: italic; margin: 0.2em 0; }\n.thlex-language-sets { margin: 0.3em 0 0.3em 1em; }\n.thlex-language-set { margin: 0.4em 0; padding-left: 0.75em; border-left: 3px solid #e0e0e0; }\n.thlex-language { font-size: 0.8em; color: #888; margin-right: 0.4em; }\n.thlex-lemma { font-weight: bold; font-family: serif; }\n.thlex-translit { color: #555; font-style: italic; font-size: 0.9em; margin-left: 0.3em; }\n.thlex-refs { font-size: 0.85em; color: #444; margin-top: 0.15em; }\n.thlex-paragraphs p { margin: 0.35em 0; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.5; }\n.thlex-image { margin: 0.5em 0; }\n.thlex-image img { max-width: 100%; height: auto; }\n.thlex-abbr { border-bottom: 1px dotted #888; cursor: help; }\n.thlex-xref { color: #1a5fb4; }\nspan[data-bnType=\"bibleReference\"] { color: #1a5fb4; }\ntable.thlex-table { border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 0.9em; margin: 0.5em 0; }\ntable.thlex-table td { padding: 0.2em 0.6em; vertical-align: top; border: 1px solid #ddd; }\ntable.thlex-table tr:first-child td { font-weight: bold; background: #f5f5f5; }\nul.thlex-index-list { margin: 0.4em 0; padding-left: 1.4em; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.6; }\nul.thlex-index-list ul { margin: 0.1em 0; padding-left: 1.4em; }\n.thlex-index-key { font-weight: bold; font-style: italic; }\n</style><h1 class=\"thlex-title\" id=\"FAUNA:5.3\"><span class=\"thlex-key\">5.3</span> Onycha</h1><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Reference:&quot;</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-sets\">\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">שְׁחֵלֶת</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(shechelet)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod30:34\">EXO 30:34</a></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Discussion:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>The Hebrew word refers to something that was used in the mixture of aromatic spices that made frankincense. This ingredient is believed to have been the nail-like covering on the foot of a mollusk (that is, a boneless sea creature) of the <em>strombus</em> type. However, a few scholars suggest that it is a type of flower.</p>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Description:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>The <em>strombus</em> mollusks are a type of sea creature something like snails, which live inside a single shell, usually spiral in structure. They have eyes set on the end of each of two stalks. Part of the mollusk extends from the shell and attaches itself to a rock or other flat surface. This is called the foot and is the means by which the mollusk moves. The foot has a nail or scale-like covering called the operculum, and when the mollusk withdraws into its shell this operculum acts as a lid, sealing the opening of the shell. It is this operculum that is thought to have been referred to by the Hebrew word <em>shechelet</em>.</p>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Translation:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>The only languages that will have a good equivalent of this Hebrew word are those spoken by people who have an intimate knowledge of sea creatures. Elsewhere it is probably best to opt for the solution followed by the translators of <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"New English Bible (1970)\">NEB</abbr> and use an expression such as “aromatic seashell” or “fragrant seashell&quot;. Another alternative would be to use a transliteration of the Hebrew <em>shechelet</em> or the Greek <em>onycha</em>, with an entry in a word list indicating what the word refers to.</p>\n</div>\n</div>",
